core_profiles.code.documentation: Generic decription of the code-specific parameters for the code that has produced this IDS

core_profiles.code.description.documentation: Short description of the software (type, purpose)

core_profiles.code.library.documentation: List of external libraries used by the code that has produced this IDS

core_profiles.code.library[:].descriptio.documentation: Short description of the software (type, purpose)

core_profiles.code.library[:].parameters.documentation: List of the code specific parameters in XML format

core_profiles.code.output_flag.documentation: Output flag : 0 means the run is successful, other values mean some difficulty has been encountered, the exact meaning is then code specific. Negative values mean the result shall not be used.

core_profiles.code.parameters.documentation: List of the code specific parameters in XML format

core_profiles.covariance.documentation: User defined covariance matrix. The covariance of various quantities can be stored here, these quantities are referred to by giving their IDS path in the rows_uri list

core_profiles.covariance.data_error_inde.documentation: Index in the error_description list for "data"

core_profiles.covariance.rows_uri.documentation: List of URIs corresponding to the rows (1st dimension) of the covariance matrix. If not all indices of a given node are used, they must be listed explicitly e.g. rows_uri(i) = pf_active:1/coil(i) will refer to a list of indices of the occurrence 1 of the pf_active IDS of this data entry. If the rows correspond to all indices of a given vector it is sufficient to give a single URI where this vector is denoted using the (:) implicit notation, e.g. rows_uri(1) = /grid_ggd(3)/grid_subset(2)/elements(:).

core_profiles.global_quantities.documentation: Various global quantities derived from the profiles

core_profiles.global_quantities.beta_pol.documentation: Poloidal beta. Defined as betap = 4 int(p dV) / [R_0 * mu_0 * Ip^2]
Index in the error_description list for "beta_pol"

core_profiles.global_quantities.beta_tor.documentation: Toroidal beta, defined as the volume-averaged total perpendicular pressure divided by (B0^2/(2*mu0)), i.e. beta_toroidal = 2 mu0 int(p dV) / V / B0^2
Index in the error_description list for "beta_tor"
Normalised toroidal beta, defined as 100 * beta_tor * a[m] * B0 [T] / ip [MA]
Index in the error_description list for "beta_tor_norm"

core_profiles.global_quantities.current_.documentation: Bootstrap current (toroidal component). Positive sign means anti-clockwise when viewed from above.
Index in the error_description list for "current_bootstrap"
Total non-inductive current (toroidal component). Positive sign means anti-clockwise when viewed from above.
Index in the error_description list for "current_non_inductive"

core_profiles.global_quantities.ejima.documentation: Ejima coefficient : resistive psi losses divided by (mu0*R*Ip). See S. Ejima et al, Nuclear Fusion, Vol.22, No.10 (1982), 1313

core_profiles.global_quantities.ejima_er.documentation: Index in the error_description list for "ejima"

core_profiles.global_quantities.energy_d.documentation: Plasma energy content = 3/2 * integral over the plasma volume of the total perpendicular pressure
Index in the error_description list for "energy_diamagnetic"

core_profiles.global_quantities.ion.documentation: Quantities related to the different ion species, in the sense of isonuclear or isomolecular sequences. The set of ion species of this array must be the same as the one defined in profiles_1d/ion, at the time slice indicated in ion_time_slice

core_profiles.global_quantities.ion[:].n.documentation: Volume averaged density of this ion species (averaged over the plasma volume up to the LCFS)
Index in the error_description list for "n_i_volume_average"

core_profiles.global_quantities.ion[:].t.documentation: Volume averaged temperature of this ion species (averaged over the plasma volume up to the LCFS)
Index in the error_description list for "t_i_volume_average"

core_profiles.global_quantities.ion_time.documentation: Time slice of the profiles_1d array used to define the ion composition of the global_quantities/ion array.
Index in the error_description list for "ion_time_slice"

core_profiles.global_quantities.ip.documentation: Total plasma current (toroidal component). Positive sign means anti-clockwise when viewed from above.

core_profiles.global_quantities.ip_error.documentation: Index in the error_description list for "ip"

core_profiles.global_quantities.li.documentation: Internal inductance. The li_3 definition is used, i.e. li_3 = 2/R0/mu0^2/Ip^2 * int(Bp^2 dV).

core_profiles.global_quantities.li_3.documentation: Internal inductance. The li_3 definition is used, i.e. li_3 = 2/R0/mu0^2/Ip^2 * int(Bp^2 dV).

core_profiles.global_quantities.li_3_err.documentation: Index in the error_description list for "li_3"

core_profiles.global_quantities.li_error.documentation: Index in the error_description list for "li"

core_profiles.global_quantities.n_e_volu.documentation: Volume averaged electron density (average over the plasma volume up to the LCFS)
Index in the error_description list for "n_e_volume_average"

core_profiles.global_quantities.resistiv.documentation: Resistive part of the poloidal flux losses, defined as the volume-averaged scalar product of the electric field and the ohmic current density, normalized by the plasma current and integrated in time from the beginning of the plasma discharge: int ( (int(E_field_tor.j_ohm_tor) dV) / Ip ) dt)
Index in the error_description list for "resistive_psi_losses"

core_profiles.global_quantities.t_e_peak.documentation: Electron temperature peaking factor, defined as the Te value at the magnetic axis divided by the volume averaged Te (average over the plasma volume up to the LCFS)
Index in the error_description list for "t_e_peaking"

core_profiles.global_quantities.t_e_volu.documentation: Volume averaged electron temperature (average over the plasma volume up to the LCFS)
Index in the error_description list for "t_e_volume_average"

core_profiles.global_quantities.t_i_aver.documentation: Ion temperature (averaged over ion species and states) peaking factor, defined as the Ti value at the magnetic axis divided by the volume averaged Ti (average over the plasma volume up to the LCFS)
Index in the error_description list for "t_i_average_peaking"

core_profiles.global_quantities.v_loop.documentation: LCFS loop voltage (positive value drives positive ohmic current that flows anti-clockwise when viewed from above)

core_profiles.global_quantities.v_loop_e.documentation: Index in the error_description list for "v_loop"

core_profiles.global_quantities.z_eff_re.documentation: Volume average plasma effective charge, estimated from the flux consumption in the ohmic phase
Index in the error_description list for "z_eff_resistive"

core_profiles.ids_properties.documentation: Interface Data Structure properties. This element identifies the node above as an IDS

core_profiles.ids_properties.comment.documentation: Any comment describing the content of this IDS

core_profiles.ids_properties.creation_da.documentation: Date at which this data has been produced

core_profiles.ids_properties.homogeneous.documentation: This node must be filled (with 0, 1, or 2) for the IDS to be valid. If 1, the time of this IDS is homogeneous, i.e. the time values for this IDS are stored in the time node just below the root of this IDS. If 0, the time values are stored in the various time fields at lower levels in the tree. In the case only constant or static nodes are filled within the IDS, homogeneous_time must be set to 2

core_profiles.ids_properties.name.documentation: User-defined name for this IDS occurrence

core_profiles.ids_properties.occurrence.description: occurrence number [NOTE: this field only exists in OMAS and is not part of the ITER PDM]

core_profiles.ids_properties.occurrence_.documentation:
Type of data contained in this occurrence
1) reconstruction : Equilibrium reconstruction
2) prediction_fixed : Equilibrium prediction, fixed boundary
3) prediction_free : Equilibrium prediction, free boundary
4) mapping : Used for mapping equilibrium results from one grid type / resolution to another, or for including variables not present in the first set such as the calculation of magnetic field of other derived parameters
Integer identifier (enumeration index within a list). Private identifier values must be indicated by a negative index.

core_profiles.ids_properties.plugins.documentation: Information about the plugins used to write/read this IDS. This structure is filled automatically by the Access Layer at GET/PUT time, no need to fill it via a user program.

core_profiles.ids_properties.plugins.inf.documentation: Plugin infrastructure used to GET the data
Short description of the software (type, purpose)
Plugin infrastructure used to PUT the data
Short description of the software (type, purpose)

core_profiles.ids_properties.plugins.nod.documentation: Set of IDS nodes for which a plugin has been applied

Plugins actually used to read back a node (potentially, multiple plugins can be applied, listed in reverse order of application). This information is filled by the plugin infrastructure during the GET operation.
Short description of the software (type, purpose)
List of the code specific parameters in XML format
Path of the node within the IDS, following the syntax given in the link below. If empty, means the plugin applies to the whole IDS.
Plugins used to PUT a node (potentially, multiple plugins can be applied, if so they are listed by order of application)
Short description of the software (type, purpose)
List of the code specific parameters in XML format
Plugins to be used to read back a node (potentially, multiple plugins can be applied, listed in reverse order of application)
Short description of the software (type, purpose)
List of the code specific parameters in XML format

core_profiles.ids_properties.provenance..documentation: Set of IDS nodes for which the provenance is given. The provenance information applies to the whole structure below the IDS node. For documenting provenance information for the whole IDS, set the size of this array of structure to 1 and leave the child "path" node empty
Path of the node within the IDS, following the syntax given in the link below. If empty, means the provenance information applies to the whole IDS.

List of sources used to import or calculate this node, identified as explained below. In case the node is the result of of a calculation / data processing, the source is an input to the process described in the "code" structure at the root of the IDS. The source can be an IDS (identified by a URI or a persitent identifier, see syntax in the link below) or non-IDS data imported directly from an non-IMAS database (identified by the command used to import the source, or the persistent identifier of the data source). Often data are obtained by a chain of processes, however only the last process input are recorded here. The full chain of provenance has then to be reconstructed recursively from the provenance information contained in the data sources.

core_profiles.ids_properties.provider.documentation: Name of the person in charge of producing this data

core_profiles.ids_properties.source.documentation: Source of the data (any comment describing the origin of the data : code, path to diagnostic signals, processing method, ...). Superseeded by the new provenance structure.

core_profiles.ids_properties.version_put.documentation: Version of the access layer package used to PUT this IDS
Version of Access Layer used to PUT this IDS
Programming language of the Access Layer high level API used to PUT this IDS
Version of Data Dictionary used to PUT this IDS

core_profiles.profiles_2d[:].grid_type.documentation:
Selection of one of a set of grid types
1) rectangular : Cylindrical R,Z ala eqdsk (R=dim1, Z=dim2). In this case the position arrays should not be filled since they are redundant with grid/dim1 and dim2.
2) inverse : Rhopolar_polar 2D polar coordinates (rho=dim1, theta=dim2) with magnetic axis as centre of grid; theta and values following the COCOS=11 convention; the polar angle is theta=atan2(z-zaxis,r-raxis)
11) inverse_psi_straight_field_line : Flux surface type with psi as radial label (dim1) and the straight-field line poloidal angle (mod(index,10)=1) (dim2); could be non-equidistant; magnetic axis as centre of grid; following the COCOS=11 convention
12) inverse_psi_equal_arc : Flux surface type with psi as radial label (dim1) and the equal arc poloidal angle (mod(index,10)=2) (dim2)
13) inverse_psi_polar : Flux surface type with psi as radial label (dim1) and the polar poloidal angle (mod(index,10)=3) (dim2); could be non-equidistant
14) inverse_psi_straight_field_line_fourier : Flux surface type with psi as radial label (dim1) and Fourier modes in the straight-field line poloidal angle (mod(index,10)=4) (dim2), could be non-equidistant; magnetic axis as centre of grid; following the COCOS=11 convention
15) inverse_psi_equal_arc_fourier : Flux surface type with psi as radial label (dim1) and Fourier modes in the equal arc poloidal angle (mod(index,10)=5) (dim2)
16) inverse_psi_polar_fourier : Flux surface type with psi as radial label (dim1) and Fourier modes in the polar poloidal angle (mod(index,10)=6) (dim2); could be non-equidistant
21) inverse_rhopolnorm_straight_field_line : Flux surface type with radial label sqrt[(psi-psi_axis)/(psi_edge-psi_axis)] (dim1) and the straight-field line poloidal angle (dim2)
22) inverse_rhopolnorm_equal_arc : Flux surface type with radial label sqrt[(psi-psi_axis)/(psi_edge-psi_axis)] (dim1) and the equal arc poloidal angle (dim2)
23) inverse_rhopolnorm_polar : Flux surface type with radial label sqrt[(psi-psi_axis)/(psi_edge-psi_axis)] (dim1) and the polar poloidal angle (dim2)
24) inverse_rhopolnorm_straight_field_line_fourier : Flux surface type with radial label sqrt[(psi-psi_axis)/(psi_edge-psi_axis)] (dim1) and Fourier modes in the straight-field line poloidal angle (dim2)
25) inverse_rhopolnorm_equal_arc_fourier : Flux surface type with radial label sqrt[(psi-psi_axis)/(psi_edge-psi_axis)] (dim1) and Fourier modes in the equal arc poloidal angle (dim2)
26) inverse_rhopolnorm_polar_fourier : Flux surface type with radial label sqrt[(psi-psi_axis)/(psi_edge-psi_axis)] (dim1) and Fourier modes in the polar poloidal angle (dim2)
31) inverse_rhotornorm_straight_field_line : Flux surface type with radial label sqrt[Phi/Phi_edge] (dim1) and the straight-field line poloidal angle (dim2)
32) inverse_rhotornorm_equal_arc : Flux surface type with radial label sqrt[Phi/Phi_edge] (dim1) and the equal arc poloidal angle (dim2)

Identifier of the statistics type
1) mean : Mean

4) kurtosis : Pearson (full) kurtosis

7) percentile_90 : 90% percentile
